# Out-of-Process Web Speech Bridge

This plan implements a hidden bridge to utilize a user's locally installed Google Chrome browser for the Web Speech API, completely bypassing Electron's API-key restrictions without adding any heavy new dependencies.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Piping App Audio to Web Speech API**
> Regarding your question: "can we pipe the audio through the app into the window so Web Speech API hears the audio we hear as well?"
> **The short answer is no, not natively.**
> The `webkitSpeechRecognition` API is fundamentally hardcoded by Google to *only* accept audio from an OS-level microphone device. It absolutely refuses to accept programmatic `MediaStream` objects, audio buffers, or piped audio feeds from your app. The engine will strictly listen to whatever is configured as your "Default Windows Microphone". 
> 
> *The only workaround* for piping specific app audio into Web Speech involves installing third-party audio drivers (like VB-Cable or VoiceMeeter) that create a "Virtual Microphone" on Windows, and setting that virtual mic as your Windows Default input. 
> 
> *This plan implements the Web Speech bridge to use your physical OS microphone normally.*

## Proposed Changes

### `main.js` (The Bridge Server)
We will stand up an extremely lightweight, dependency-free HTTP server running internally on `127.0.0.1` inside the Electron main process.
- **GET `/`**: Serves a dynamic HTML payload containing the `webkitSpeechRecognition` client-side JavaScript.
- **POST `/result`**: An endpoint where the Chrome browser will dump recognized text blocks via `fetch()`. The main process instantly forwards this data to the BibleCast renderer via `webContents.send('whisper:progress', ...)` or equivalent.
- **Chrome Spawner Engine**: Create an IPC handler `ipcMain.handle('chrome:start-bridge')` that searches standard Windows directories for `chrome.exe`, and runs it via `child_process.spawn()` with critical flags: `--app=http://127.0.0.1:<PORT>/`, `--use-fake-ui-for-media-stream`, and `--window-position=-2000,-2000` (to hide it off-screen). 

### `preload.js`
- [MODIFY] Expose bindings for the new Chrome bridge to the renderer:
  - `startChromeBridge()`
  - `stopChromeBridge()`

### `src/renderer/renderer.js`
- [MODIFY] Wire the "Web Speech API" settings option to trigger `startChromeBridge()` instead of the standard `recognition.start()` which currently fails in Electron.
- [MODIFY] Add cleanup logic to kill the Chrome process appropriately when the user hits "Stop Listening" or closes the app.

## Open Questions

None at this time. The architecture utilizes native `http` and `child_process` libraries so it introduces zero new heavy NPM dependencies.

## Verification Plan

### Manual Verification
1. Open BibleCast and select "Web Speech API" from the drop-down.
2. Click **Start Listening**.
3. Verify that a hidden Chrome process has spawned in Task Manager and Windows shows the "microphone in use" system tray icon.
4. Speak into the default microphone and watch the transcription accurately appear in the BibleCast text feed.
5. Click **Stop Listening**. Confirm the Chrome sub-process correctly halts / self-destructs.
